Task: Removing unsafe pointer and make vector element comparison parallel

 <p>I have a little parallelizing question.</p>
<p>I want to implement a trait function for A, below, which iterates over its <code>Vec&lt;B&gt;</code> field, and for each elements looks for <em>all the following elements</em>, and modify the Vec contained by <em>both</em> elements if a certain criterion is met.</p>
<p>The code below can also be found <a href="https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&amp;mode=debug&amp;edition=2024&amp;gist=8b847b5d04de92abee14ff69666c988c" rel="nofollow noreferrer">on the playground</a>:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>#[derive(Debug, Default, Clone)]
struct B {
    r: Vec&lt;f64&gt;,
    v: Vec&lt;f64&gt;,
    f: Vec&lt;f64&gt;,
    nb: Vec&lt;usize&gt;
}

impl B {
    pub fn criterion(&amp;self, other: &amp;B) -&gt; f64 {
        let dx = self.r[0] - other.r[0];
        let dy = self.r[1] - other.r[1];
        let dz = self.r[2] - other.r[2];

        dx * dx + dy * dy + dz * dz
    }
}

#[derive(Debug, Default, Clone)]
struct A {
    elems: Vec&lt;B&gt;,
    cutoff: f64,
}

impl A {
    pub fn get_nelems(&amp;self) -&gt; usize {
        self.elems.len()
    }

    pub fn build_lists(&amp;mut self) {
        let nelems = self.get_nelems(); // number of elements in Vec&lt;B&gt;
        let ptr = self.elems.as_ptr(); // a ptr

        self.elems
            .iter_mut()
            .enumerate()
            .for_each(|(i, elem_i)| {
                elem_i.nb = Vec::new();

                for j in 0..nelems {
                    if i == j {
                        continue;
                    }

                    let elem_j = unsafe { &amp;*ptr.add(j) }; // I don't like this.

                    if elem_i.criterion(&amp;elem_j) &lt; self.cutoff {
                        elem_i.nb.push(j);
                    }
                }
            });
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>I have three questions:</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Is it possible to implement a solution that does not use <code>unsafe</code> pointers without making copies of the <code>Vec&lt;B&gt;</code> or what it contains?</p>
</li>
<li><p>Is there a way to modify <code>elem_j</code> the same way <code>elem_i</code> is modified if criterion is met? For now the loop goes through the whole Vec for each elements.</p>
</li>
<li><p>How can we implement a parallel version of this? I tried to use <code>par_iter_mut</code> from <code>rayon</code> but it tells me that <code>* const B</code> does not implement <code>Sync</code> and <code>Send</code>. Is there another library I could use.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>I know solutions in C++, but here I reach my limits concerning Rust ownership mechanism.</p>


